AB  - Abstract This paper examines the effect of ethnic ties on venture capital ( VC ) stage financing in the US market. After dealing with the endogeneity problem, the paper shows that VC investors who share ethnicity with an entrepreneur tend to finance the company using a smaller number of rounds, longer durations between successive rounds, and a larger amount in each round. The effect is more pronounced when the startup company and the VC firm are not located in the same city or the VC s lack industry‐specific expertise. My findings also suggest that such trust due to co‐ethnicity leads to bad investment performance.
